<span id="freeTextContainer15606874324244937240">OH MY GOSH a goal I&apos;ve had since I got Goodreads was to never rate a book one star. I thought, <i>Well, the author put so much effort into this magnificent piece of work, so why would I give it only one star? Surely, there&apos;s no book I will hate, right?</i> WELL, I didn&apos;t like this book at all! I did not enjoy the author&apos;s voice, the way the book is written. I felt like it was <i> too</i> descriptive. As in, every sentence became annoying. Oh, and don&apos;t get me started with the characters. I found them too stup</span>
  <span id="freeText15606874324244937240" style="display:none">OH MY GOSH a goal I've had since I got Goodreads was to never rate a book one star. I thought, <i>Well, the author put so much effort into this magnificent piece of work, so why would I give it only one star? Surely, there's no book I will hate, right?</i> WELL, I didn't like this book at all! I did not enjoy the author's voice, the way the book is written. I felt like it was <i> too</i> descriptive. As in, every sentence became annoying. Oh, and don't get me started with the characters. I found them too stupid to take seriously. The only thing I think the book did well was originality. I've never read a book with this concept before, and it was interesting to watch how the author shaped this world and played with the idea of everyone knowing when they will die. It was fun and new, but not for me; sorry. <br /></span>
